Thank you, Ilaria, and thank you all for getting up early to

32
00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:40.540
join this session.

33
00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:45.840
So my topic will be about co-evolution of tumor and the stroma

34
00:01:45.880 --> 00:01:49.720
microenvironment during the progression of cancer metastasis, the dynamic

35
00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:53.740
evolution during different stages of metastasis, especially the

36
00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:54.720
organ sites of bone.

37
00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.760
So one of the interesting phenomena that clinicians and scientists

38
00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:03.700
know about metastasis is that it's actually a very inefficient event.

39
00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:08.560
In patients, you could be seeing millions of the tumor cell disseminated every

40
00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:12.240
day, but only a tiny fraction of them eventually make metastasis.

41
00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:16.600
In the mice, we also know that not all tumors are created equal.

42
00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:20.320
The same cell line, you can select for variants that have high

43
00:02:20.329 --> 00:02:23.870
propensity to metastasize to different organ sites, and those

44
00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:26.740
constitute only a small fraction of those tumor as well.

45
00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:30.700
So then the key question is if all tumor in the same patient or in the same

46
00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:34.200
cell line harbor the same mutations in

47
00:02:34.260 --> 00:02:37.720
oncogenes and tumor suppressors, what makes certain tumor cell

48
00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:40.060
metastatic? So over the years,

49
00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:44.840
the field have come to a realization that a lot of the

50
00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.520
genes, the so-called metastasis genes, or I would prefer

51
00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:52.240
to call them cancer fitness genes, are the ones that not

52
00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:56.120
really play a key role in driving initial events of oncogenesis.

53
00:02:56.180 --> 00:03:00.000
But those genes allow the tumor cell to

54
00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:03.720
adapt to increasing level of stress during

55
00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:07.580
early invasion, dissemination, survival in circulation,

56
00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:11.980
and then seeding in distant organ and then eventual outgrowths.

57
00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:17.060
In each step, the tumor cell are facing tremendous level of

58
00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.930
stress from the immune attack, from oxidative stress, hypoxia, replicative

59
00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:24.160
stress, nutrient shortage. They also have to

60
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.020
adapt to different metabolic needs as well.

61
00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:27.940
So

62
00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:32.300
how does metastatic tumor cell achieve that? There are two ways.

63
00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:36.200
One is through gaining of those so-called cancer fitness genes,

64
00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:40.840
often through epigenetic changes to elevate expression rather

65
00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:44.320
than sequence mutations. And second is the

66
00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:48.300
dependency of the microenvironment, the so-called niche, different niche during

67
00:03:48.580 --> 00:03:51.760
progression and metastasis. And this is not a new idea.

68
00:03:51.769 --> 00:03:55.720
Actually, more than 120 years ago, Stephen Paget already

69
00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:59.520
proposed this so-called seed and soil hypothesis that beautifully

70
00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:03.240
explained the idea even without a clear mechanistic insight.

71
00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:08.000
So one of the phenomena that he noted in

72
00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:11.460
his original publication back in 1889

73
00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:13.980
is that he noticed

74
00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:18.661
bone is among the most frequent organ sites that are affected in

75
00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:22.340
patients with breast cancer. And he noted that this could

76
00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:26.300
not be explained by just the blood flow pattern alone, and that's

77
00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:30.280
why he come up with this idea of the so-called seed and soil interactions,

78
00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:34.760
even though 100 years ago, there is no tool to try to figure out what

79
00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:37.320
happened during metastatic progression in bone.

80
00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:38.280
So

81
00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.580
in bone metastasis, there are a series of questions that we

82
00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:45.940
ask, and I will try to cover in my short 20-minute talk.

83
00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:49.080
What make bone such a fertile soil?

84
00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.140
What are the genes in driving bone metastasis in tumor cell?

85
00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:56.000
What consists the bone metastatic niche?

86
00:04:56.620 --> 00:05:00.380
And also the spatiotemporal events of seed and

87
00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:02.650
soil interaction. How does the soil

88
00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:07.260
support the seeds, and what does the seeds do to the soil?

89
00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:11.300
Do they change them as well? And what are systemic complication of

90
00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:14.380
such interaction, and how does interaction affect

91
00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:18.120
the treatments response of metastatic cancer?

92
00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:21.780
And they are often more resistant to all different kind of standard

93
00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:22.260
treatments.

94
00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:27.200
So if you look at a microscopic image of bone metastasis, this

95
00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:30.160
is looking at human breast cancer metastasis to bone.

96
00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.140
You see many different stromal cell involved.

97
00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:38.200
So tumor cells are here. What you often see is lining the bone

98
00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:40.940
surface are a large number of these large,

99
00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:44.020
multinucleated cell. Those are not tumor cells.

100
00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:48.100
These are osteoclast, and they break down the bone to

101
00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:52.020
allow continued expansion, and also that breaking down bone release a

102
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.580
lot of bone growth factors to stimulate further

103
00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:59.580
malignancy of the tumor. There are also other bone cell type like osteocytes and

104
00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:03.140
osteoblasts. They are bone building cells, but they also participate in

105
00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:05.180
pathogenesis of bone metastasis as well.

106
00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:08.020
And then we also see a lot of cells in the hematopoietic

107
00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:11.324
lineage.So the question then is, what do they

108
00:06:11.364 --> 00:06:13.964
do in the pathogenesis of bone metastasis?

109
00:06:14.504 --> 00:06:18.484
So in bone, this is a major hematopoietic organ, and we know that there are some

110
00:06:18.524 --> 00:06:22.384
pre-existing niche in bone, including the so-called interstitial

111
00:06:22.464 --> 00:06:25.444
niche, including osteoclasts, osteoblasts and

112
00:06:25.863 --> 00:06:29.844
mesenchymal niche cell. There's also perivascular niche that

113
00:06:29.904 --> 00:06:33.764
is very important to support the hematopoietic stem cell

114
00:06:33.844 --> 00:06:34.324
function.

115
00:06:35.124 --> 00:06:39.084
So one obvious guess we have is that maybe

116
00:06:39.124 --> 00:06:42.814
the tumor cells just take advantage of this pre-existing niche for initial

117
00:06:42.904 --> 00:06:46.264
seeding, but also continuous growth expansion.

118
00:06:46.404 --> 00:06:50.284
Also bone, of course, contain a lot of hematopoietic niche cell and other

119
00:06:50.504 --> 00:06:51.384
cell type as well,

120
00:06:52.364 --> 00:06:53.144
like nerve,

121
00:06:53.984 --> 00:06:57.884
adipocytes, fibroblasts. They all could participate

122
00:06:57.984 --> 00:07:01.744
in bone metastasis. The question then is to figure out what are the

123
00:07:01.764 --> 00:07:05.484
components of the bone metastasis niche, and what do they do to support the growth

124
00:07:05.564 --> 00:07:06.864
of the metastatic soil.

125
00:07:08.004 --> 00:07:11.924
So I'm going to show you some examples of how tumor cell at different stage of

126
00:07:11.944 --> 00:07:14.984
metastasis take advantage of this existing niche.

127
00:07:15.984 --> 00:07:17.024
So tumor cell can

128
00:07:17.944 --> 00:07:21.504
initially home to the bone using chemokine

129
00:07:22.144 --> 00:07:24.844
chemotaxis, similar to leukocyte trafficking.

130
00:07:24.964 --> 00:07:28.414
So for example, tumor can express high level chemokine receptor CXCL4,

131
00:07:29.224 --> 00:07:30.284
and then get attracted to

132
00:07:31.564 --> 00:07:34.904
organ sites in bone that produce a high level of

133
00:07:35.224 --> 00:07:36.724
chemokine CXCL12.

134
00:07:37.644 --> 00:07:41.544
Also, some of the same adhesion molecule involving

135
00:07:41.584 --> 00:07:45.264
leukocyte trafficking like E-selectin, which is also very important to support

136
00:07:45.304 --> 00:07:48.764
hematopoietic stem cell function,

137
00:07:49.444 --> 00:07:52.224
also are utilized for early seeding of bone metastasis.

138
00:07:52.324 --> 00:07:55.904
As you can see in here, this is GFP-positive tumor cell.

139
00:07:55.984 --> 00:07:59.804
In early micro metastasis, they are often attached very

140
00:07:59.844 --> 00:08:03.804
close to the vasculature. And the reason is they are taking advantage of

141
00:08:03.864 --> 00:08:07.004
the E-selectin that is highly expressed in the bone vasculature.

142
00:08:07.624 --> 00:08:11.164
And what does E-selectin do? Of course, one obvious function is

143
00:08:11.204 --> 00:08:14.704
adhesion, slow down the tumor, and facilitate extravasation.

144
00:08:15.204 --> 00:08:19.084
But biologically, attachment to E-selectin also

145
00:08:19.104 --> 00:08:22.624
induce a phenomenon called mesenchymal to epithelial transition, because

146
00:08:22.664 --> 00:08:25.644
oftentimes when tumor disseminate from the primary tumor,

147
00:08:26.544 --> 00:08:28.724
cytokines like TGF-beta induce EMT.

148
00:08:29.004 --> 00:08:31.684
EMT also increase the stemness of cancer cell.

149
00:08:32.504 --> 00:08:36.365
When they disseminate to distant organ, we often know that the tumor cell

150
00:08:36.444 --> 00:08:39.744
often undergo the reverse process, mesenchymal to epithelial transition.

151
00:08:39.804 --> 00:08:43.324
This is required for proliferation of tumor as secondary tumors.

152
00:08:43.764 --> 00:08:47.593
But that conflict with the idea that EMT promote stemness, MET

153
00:08:48.104 --> 00:08:51.944
reverse that. So by engaging E-selectin, this

154
00:08:52.004 --> 00:08:55.784
induce a non-canonical MET to allow the tumor cell to gain the

155
00:08:56.244 --> 00:09:00.144
epithelial phenotype. And at the same time, E-selectin engagement stimulate Wnt

156
00:09:00.224 --> 00:09:03.644
signaling activity that allow the tumor cell to maintain stemness.

157
00:09:03.724 --> 00:09:07.504
And you can see that indeed, in those bone metastasis in

158
00:09:07.544 --> 00:09:11.524
area of high vasculature density, the tumor

159
00:09:11.564 --> 00:09:15.563
cell have high Wnt signaling activity, as shown by this Wnt reporter.

160
00:09:16.024 --> 00:09:19.884
And this allow the tumor cell to gain epithelial phenotype and at the same

161
00:09:19.964 --> 00:09:22.744
time maintain high stemness for early seeding.

162
00:09:23.964 --> 00:09:25.964
The problem is in the late stage of

163
00:09:27.464 --> 00:09:31.064
metastasis, often it switch to a osteolytic

164
00:09:31.704 --> 00:09:34.424
phenotype that actually Wnt signaling inhibited that.

165
00:09:34.524 --> 00:09:37.344
So there need to be a switch of signaling state.

166
00:09:37.984 --> 00:09:41.864
So at different stage of bone metastasis progression, other

167
00:09:42.844 --> 00:09:46.204
stromal niche is utilized, especially the interstitial niche.

168
00:09:46.464 --> 00:09:50.044
So Sean Zhang and others have shown that by engaging

169
00:09:50.104 --> 00:09:51.093
osteoblast and

170
00:09:51.924 --> 00:09:55.804
using this so-called heterotypic cadherin interaction between E-cadherin

171
00:09:55.844 --> 00:09:59.804
tumor cell and N-cadherin in the osteoblast, this stimulate the

172
00:09:59.884 --> 00:10:01.624
growth of early seeded tumors.

173
00:10:03.004 --> 00:10:06.604
And also later on, once the tumor cells start to

174
00:10:06.644 --> 00:10:10.564
engage the osteoclast, this could impart through the

175
00:10:10.624 --> 00:10:13.764
osteoblast induce cytokines like RANKL, M-CSF.

176
00:10:14.444 --> 00:10:18.424
The tumor cell also produce other factors like JAG1 that stimulate

177
00:10:18.484 --> 00:10:22.174
osteoclast maturation. That leads to breakdown of bone

178
00:10:22.224 --> 00:10:26.084
matrix, and release bone-derived growth factors

179
00:10:26.184 --> 00:10:30.104
like TGF-beta. TGF-beta is abundantly stored in bone matrix in

180
00:10:30.144 --> 00:10:33.044
an inactive form. And breakdown of the

181
00:10:34.144 --> 00:10:37.384
bone matrix by osteoclast and protease activity of the tumor cell

182
00:10:37.904 --> 00:10:41.874
release active TGF-beta. And we know this is happening because by

183
00:10:41.904 --> 00:10:45.704
histology, you can see that in this bone metastasis section, you can

184
00:10:45.744 --> 00:10:49.584
see that the tumor that are facing the bone matrix

185
00:10:49.684 --> 00:10:52.264
have the most intense staining of phospho-Smad2.

186
00:10:52.324 --> 00:10:54.884
That's the indication of active TGF-beta signaling.

187
00:10:55.584 --> 00:10:59.284
So indeed, there's a positive feedback from the

188
00:10:59.384 --> 00:11:02.224
soil to the seeds via

189
00:11:02.904 --> 00:11:04.744
bone-derived TGF-beta growth factor.

190
00:11:06.104 --> 00:11:09.464
And so TGF-beta stimulate the increased expression of

191
00:11:09.524 --> 00:11:13.164
JAG1 in the tumor cell. JAG1 can

192
00:11:13.184 --> 00:11:17.174
directly stimulate osteoclast maturation from its monocytic precursor,

193
00:11:17.744 --> 00:11:19.684
and also stimulate production of

194
00:11:20.584 --> 00:11:24.524
tumor promoter growth factor like IL-11 and CTGF from

195
00:11:24.564 --> 00:11:28.064
osteoblast. So in this case, through engaging

196
00:11:28.144 --> 00:11:32.064
TGF-beta, JAG1, Notch feedback loop, the tumor cell

197
00:11:32.104 --> 00:11:35.464
can actively engage different soil components and respond to

198
00:11:35.544 --> 00:11:37.684
soil-derived growth factors like TGF-beta.

199
00:11:38.764 --> 00:11:42.364
What we also found is that JAG1 could also be

200
00:11:42.484 --> 00:11:46.304
stimulated in high expressing in osteoblast, and that

201
00:11:46.384 --> 00:11:48.444
in turn protect the tumor cell

202
00:11:49.244 --> 00:11:52.804
from chemotherapy. So chemotherapy induce JAG1

203
00:11:52.844 --> 00:11:56.344
expressing in osteoblast, and that protect tumor cell from

204
00:11:56.424 --> 00:11:57.844
chemotherapy-induced cell death.

205
00:11:58.434 --> 00:12:01.844
This makes the tumor bone metastasis resistant to

206
00:12:01.864 --> 00:12:02.554
chemotherapy.

207
00:12:03.404 --> 00:12:06.444
So that is the reason that we,

208
00:12:07.504 --> 00:12:11.424
in collaboration with Amgen, developed this neutralizing antibody 15d11

209
00:12:11.484 --> 00:12:14.504
that target both tumor-derived JAG1 and

210
00:12:14.584 --> 00:12:18.328
osteoblast-derived JAG1 in response to chemotherapy.And the

211
00:12:18.428 --> 00:12:19.688
benefit is obvious.

212
00:12:20.568 --> 00:12:23.868
This is the mouse experiment looking at bone metastasis development by

213
00:12:23.948 --> 00:12:26.308
bioluminescent imaging in large scale.

214
00:12:27.188 --> 00:12:30.928
You can see without any treatment, the tumor grows exponentially in bone.

215
00:12:31.568 --> 00:12:35.427
With single treatment of either chemotherapy or JAK1 neutralizing antibody,

216
00:12:35.488 --> 00:12:38.728
there's a 10% decrease of bone metastasis development.

217
00:12:39.228 --> 00:12:42.818
But a combined treatment leads to nearly 100% reduction of bone

218
00:12:42.868 --> 00:12:45.648
metastasis. So in not only targeting

219
00:12:45.748 --> 00:12:49.348
stroma interaction, not only

220
00:12:49.388 --> 00:12:52.908
directly inhibit osteolytic bone metastasis growth, but also make the

221
00:12:52.948 --> 00:12:55.808
tumor more sensitive to chemotherapy.

222
00:12:57.428 --> 00:13:01.308
So as I mentioned, there's a switch from initial seeding

223
00:13:01.688 --> 00:13:05.008
in the perivascular niche of the tumor with high Wnt activity,

224
00:13:05.708 --> 00:13:09.388
possibly induced by E-selectin engagement, to later stage of

225
00:13:09.408 --> 00:13:10.948
high TGF-beta active state,

226
00:13:11.888 --> 00:13:15.748
possibly because of osteolytic release of TGF-beta

227
00:13:15.788 --> 00:13:17.208
from the bone matrix.

228
00:13:18.068 --> 00:13:21.748
So there's a switch of activity. So how does this switch happen?

229
00:13:22.408 --> 00:13:26.008
So what we figure out is that in response to TGF-beta,

230
00:13:26.588 --> 00:13:30.488
the tumor cell also upregulate a gene called DACH1, which

231
00:13:30.498 --> 00:13:33.888
form a biomolecular condensate, or the so-called phase

232
00:13:34.188 --> 00:13:37.988
separation. As you can see in here, this is a DACH1 tdTomato

233
00:13:38.788 --> 00:13:42.368
in breast cancer cell line forming these condensates.

234
00:13:42.488 --> 00:13:45.548
And this condensate essentially secreted

235
00:13:46.228 --> 00:13:50.148
casein kinase 2, which is essential for supporting

236
00:13:50.188 --> 00:13:53.808
Wnt signaling, and essentially suppress Wnt signaling

237
00:13:53.828 --> 00:13:57.738
activity. So by virtue of increased TGF-beta release, forming

238
00:13:57.768 --> 00:14:01.688
a condensate, and suppressing Wnt, the tumor cells switch from

239
00:14:01.748 --> 00:14:04.758
a high Wnt initial seeding state to high

240
00:14:04.828 --> 00:14:07.108
TGF-beta later osteolytic state.

241
00:14:07.468 --> 00:14:10.228
So you can see the progression of different signaling states during different

242
00:14:10.288 --> 00:14:11.668
stages of bone metastasis development.

243
00:14:12.388 --> 00:14:16.008
So I already show you some of the preexisting niche, the

244
00:14:16.068 --> 00:14:20.028
osteo niche and the perivascular niche, that was utilized

245
00:14:20.048 --> 00:14:23.468
by tumor cell at different stages of metastatic progression.

246
00:14:24.268 --> 00:14:27.728
There's still a big black hole in terms of what are the cell types, stromal

247
00:14:27.767 --> 00:14:29.728
components, that could be engaged by tumor.

248
00:14:29.788 --> 00:14:33.258
Tumor could create their own niche as well during the progression of

249
00:14:33.308 --> 00:14:36.628
metastasis. And that previously was difficult to study

250
00:14:37.228 --> 00:14:41.088
because we don't know what are the component of the stroma, and we are not able to

251
00:14:41.128 --> 00:14:42.808
identify their functional importance.

252
00:14:43.268 --> 00:14:45.788
And this start to change with the technology development.

253
00:14:46.068 --> 00:14:49.608
One is with the single-cell sequencing technology, and second

254
00:14:49.968 --> 00:14:53.548
is with the development of niche labeling technology, including the

255
00:14:54.068 --> 00:14:57.028
technology developed by our chair, Larry Menanke,

256
00:14:57.968 --> 00:14:58.708
several years ago,

257
00:14:59.528 --> 00:15:03.527
using secreted mCherry. And she kindly shared this contract with us

258
00:15:04.408 --> 00:15:05.808
to study bone metastasis.

259
00:15:06.628 --> 00:15:10.148
So what we did in here is, we engineered a tumor cell

260
00:15:10.168 --> 00:15:13.908
to express GFP, so they are green. They also express a

261
00:15:13.968 --> 00:15:17.908
secreted form of mCherry that also have a lipid permeating peptide

262
00:15:17.928 --> 00:15:20.728
that allow them to penetrate the membrane of the neighboring cell.

263
00:15:21.288 --> 00:15:25.088
So the tumor will produce this secreted mCherry, diffuse to

264
00:15:26.268 --> 00:15:30.088
short distance, and then taken up by the neighboring niche cell.

265
00:15:30.148 --> 00:15:34.088
So this allow you to label a niche cell, and then you can sort and to do

266
00:15:34.128 --> 00:15:37.828
single-cell sequencing. So you have to do this combination of technology to

267
00:15:37.888 --> 00:15:41.208
specifically identify, especially very rare cells.

268
00:15:41.408 --> 00:15:45.028
Because if you just isolate all the cell in bone marrow, do single-cell sequencing,

269
00:15:45.468 --> 00:15:48.448
you will miss those rare cells because they're in small number.

270
00:15:48.818 --> 00:15:52.148
So even if they change significantly in number, you're not going to catch

271
00:15:52.228 --> 00:15:56.158
them. So this just to show you that in bone metastas, indeed, you have

272
00:15:56.188 --> 00:15:59.168
this double positive tumor cell, and they secrete

273
00:15:59.288 --> 00:16:02.848
mCherry that diffuse up to about 80 micrometer.

274
00:16:03.528 --> 00:16:07.328
And it will be taken up by the neighboring niche cell and painting in red.

275
00:16:07.418 --> 00:16:11.008
And then we can then sort them out as single positive, mCherry

276
00:16:11.048 --> 00:16:11.608
positive

277
00:16:12.608 --> 00:16:15.968
niche cell. The distal cell, they are far away from the

278
00:16:16.828 --> 00:16:20.318
tumor, will not be labeled, so they'll be a negative cell as

279
00:16:20.348 --> 00:16:24.268
control. And then we also have additional control from the same bone marrow

280
00:16:24.308 --> 00:16:27.328
cell from normal healthy mice without bone metastasis.

281
00:16:28.308 --> 00:16:29.868
Then we can do single-cell sequencing

282
00:16:30.868 --> 00:16:34.788
to see what are the enrichment or depletion of certain stromal component.

283
00:16:34.828 --> 00:16:36.948
They are very close to the bone metastatic niche.

284
00:16:37.628 --> 00:16:41.528
And this is essentially a near complete catalog of the

285
00:16:41.568 --> 00:16:43.708
niche component in bone metastasis.

286
00:16:44.388 --> 00:16:48.368
So one of the interesting observation that all the adaptive immunity

287
00:16:48.828 --> 00:16:52.268
cells, the B cell, T cell, DCs are depleted

288
00:16:53.108 --> 00:16:56.808
in bone metastatic niche, essentially making the bone metastas immune code.

289
00:16:56.828 --> 00:17:00.508
And this is consistent with the observation that bone metastasis are

290
00:17:00.708 --> 00:17:04.268
often much more resistant to immunotherapy compared to primary tumors.

291
00:17:04.618 --> 00:17:06.689
And this is maybe partially explain that.

292
00:17:07.429 --> 00:17:09.828
We also see enrichment of certain cell types.

293
00:17:09.888 --> 00:17:12.368
For example, basophil is enriched in the niche in red.

294
00:17:13.308 --> 00:17:17.209
And more importantly, this particular population of macrophage

295
00:17:17.368 --> 00:17:21.068
that we call macrophage C, as you can see in here, is highly enriched in the

296
00:17:21.168 --> 00:17:21.429
niche,

297
00:17:22.348 --> 00:17:26.328
but not in the distal or the less in the distal or the healthy

298
00:17:27.008 --> 00:17:30.708
normal bone marrow. They exist, but much less number, in

299
00:17:30.948 --> 00:17:31.688
total number. So

300
00:17:32.808 --> 00:17:36.588
in fact, when bone metastas form, Mac C actually only increase

301
00:17:36.628 --> 00:17:39.608
slightly in total number, but they change their location.

302
00:17:39.648 --> 00:17:41.158
They become recruited on the niche.

303
00:17:41.488 --> 00:17:44.768
And that's why you need both the niche labeling and single-cell sequencing to

304
00:17:44.828 --> 00:17:46.888
identify this particular enrichment.

305
00:17:47.788 --> 00:17:50.208
So we are curious about what is this

306
00:17:51.728 --> 00:17:55.588
population, what is this particular Mac C population that make them

307
00:17:55.668 --> 00:17:59.488
unique, and maybe they play a role in bone metastasis. So we need to isolate them.

308
00:18:00.188 --> 00:18:02.608
And we noticed that they express three

309
00:18:03.448 --> 00:18:06.938
cell surface markers in high level, VK1 and

310
00:18:06.968 --> 00:18:10.508
CD163 adhesion molecules, and they're actually functionally

311
00:18:10.588 --> 00:18:14.328
important not only as markers. And they also have chemokine receptor

312
00:18:14.348 --> 00:18:17.708
CCR3. And this is actually the chemokine that allow the

313
00:18:17.728 --> 00:18:21.727
chemotactic attraction of those Mac C

314
00:18:21.788 --> 00:18:25.648
to the bone metastas, because tumor cell express CCL5 as a

315
00:18:25.668 --> 00:18:29.452
ligand in high level.So we can use these three

316
00:18:29.552 --> 00:18:32.452
markers to isolate the triple positive

317
00:18:32.752 --> 00:18:36.532
bone marrow macrophages and compare them to

318
00:18:36.652 --> 00:18:40.612
general macrophages in both the normal and the bone metastatic

319
00:18:41.272 --> 00:18:44.712
bone marrow from the mice. And the top enriched

320
00:18:44.772 --> 00:18:48.272
signature is consistently the so-called heme metabolism.

321
00:18:49.072 --> 00:18:52.052
So when you look at the genes that are highly enriched,

322
00:18:53.152 --> 00:18:56.722
they are genes involved in iron transport, like for

323
00:18:56.772 --> 00:19:00.512
example, transferrin receptor, which is important for iron import,

324
00:19:00.732 --> 00:19:04.512
and ferroportin, which is important for iron export, and mitoferrin,

325
00:19:04.872 --> 00:19:08.472
which is important for transporting iron into the mitochondria for metabolism.

326
00:19:09.432 --> 00:19:11.332
Ferritin for iron storage and so on.

327
00:19:12.172 --> 00:19:15.672
But also genes involving heme metabolism, heme synthesis, genes

328
00:19:15.692 --> 00:19:19.412
involving cell adhesion, including the two adhesion markers that I mentioned

329
00:19:19.452 --> 00:19:23.232
earlier, CD163 and VCAM-1, highly expressed in those

330
00:19:23.372 --> 00:19:26.812
MacC population. And then also transcription factors like

331
00:19:26.892 --> 00:19:30.592
S**C that is highly expressed. And S**C rings a

332
00:19:30.692 --> 00:19:34.392
bell because this is a transcription factor that specifically

333
00:19:34.412 --> 00:19:38.132
expressed in a particular macrophage that is well known in

334
00:19:38.392 --> 00:19:41.632
red blood cell generation, the so-called iron-enriched,

335
00:19:43.492 --> 00:19:46.952
iron recycling macrophage or erythropoiesis island macrophage.

336
00:19:47.492 --> 00:19:49.012
So what is EBI macrophage?

337
00:19:50.572 --> 00:19:54.552
So in our hematopoietic system, the cell dies every 120 days, so

338
00:19:54.592 --> 00:19:58.432
we have to replace the red blood cell very frequently every day.

339
00:19:58.892 --> 00:20:02.692
And we need our heme to make the hemoglobin for new red blood cells.

340
00:20:03.552 --> 00:20:04.272
The iron

341
00:20:05.592 --> 00:20:08.012
mostly cannot come just from the diet alone.

342
00:20:08.052 --> 00:20:11.872
That makes up only about 5% of the iron that we

343
00:20:11.912 --> 00:20:15.872
need every day. Most of the iron comes from the recycling of dying red blood cells

344
00:20:15.932 --> 00:20:19.392
by the macrophage, this so-called erythropoiesis island

345
00:20:19.412 --> 00:20:23.372
macrophage. So those EBI macrophages are nursing

346
00:20:23.432 --> 00:20:27.172
cells. They use those adhesion molecules to attach to

347
00:20:27.272 --> 00:20:31.192
immature erytroblasts and facilitate not only the

348
00:20:31.272 --> 00:20:34.852
iron transport, recycling iron to those maturing red blood

349
00:20:34.872 --> 00:20:38.541
cells, but also facilitate the process of enucleation, kick out the

350
00:20:38.592 --> 00:20:41.452
nuclei to allow the maturation of macrophage.

351
00:20:41.852 --> 00:20:45.672
Without the EBI macrophage, the erytroblasts will remain

352
00:20:45.692 --> 00:20:47.552
immature, and then we lose

353
00:20:48.532 --> 00:20:50.992
mature red blood cells, and the mice will become anemic.

354
00:20:51.442 --> 00:20:55.432
And that explains why when patients have bone metastasis, they

355
00:20:55.672 --> 00:20:57.512
often become anemic. So

356
00:20:58.552 --> 00:21:02.212
that's the hypothesis. When tumor metastasizes to bone, they

357
00:21:02.312 --> 00:21:06.172
use chemokines to attract the EBI macrophage away from

358
00:21:06.232 --> 00:21:09.792
the EBI erythropoiesis islands and deplete them for

359
00:21:10.132 --> 00:21:13.452
red blood cell generation. And we can clearly see that.

360
00:21:13.492 --> 00:21:14.612
This is the normal bone marrow.

361
00:21:15.512 --> 00:21:19.192
The blue cells are the iron-enriched EBI

362
00:21:19.292 --> 00:21:19.932
macrophage.

363
00:21:20.912 --> 00:21:24.552
When the tumor forms in here in gray, they attract those EBI

364
00:21:24.592 --> 00:21:28.492
macrophages to the bone metastasis and away from the EBIs.

365
00:21:28.572 --> 00:21:32.201
And the consequence is the change of the maturation

366
00:21:32.472 --> 00:21:36.252
trajectory. So erytroblasts go through six

367
00:21:36.332 --> 00:21:39.752
stages of maturation. The first four stages still contain the nuclei.

368
00:21:40.132 --> 00:21:43.752
The erythropoiesis island macrophage supply the iron and also

369
00:21:43.852 --> 00:21:47.692
facilitate enucleation to become reticulocytes and

370
00:21:47.732 --> 00:21:51.512
then mature erythrocytes. So if you count by flow

371
00:21:51.552 --> 00:21:55.352
cytometry, the cells at different stages, you can see that the last two

372
00:21:55.492 --> 00:21:55.812
stages,

373
00:21:57.372 --> 00:22:01.292
the mice with bone metastasis are depleting of stage five and stage

374
00:22:01.392 --> 00:22:03.112
six, and that's why they become anemic.

375
00:22:03.572 --> 00:22:07.312
The first four stages, even though the total number didn't change, the

376
00:22:07.352 --> 00:22:09.412
distribution pattern significantly changed.

377
00:22:09.612 --> 00:22:13.352
So in a normal, healthy bone marrow, stages one to four have a very

378
00:22:13.412 --> 00:22:15.872
typical one to two to four to eight ratio.

379
00:22:16.632 --> 00:22:20.112
When the mice develop bone metastasis, they're stuck in phase four

380
00:22:20.492 --> 00:22:24.112
because they don't have enough iron, and we know that because when they don't have

381
00:22:24.192 --> 00:22:27.882
enough iron, they express high level of iron importers,

382
00:22:28.052 --> 00:22:30.792
screening for iron in all those cells.

383
00:22:31.512 --> 00:22:35.392
And they also cannot take out nuclei, so they're stuck in phase four.

384
00:22:37.092 --> 00:22:39.492
We also know that indeed this is the case.

385
00:22:39.772 --> 00:22:43.572
So in phase four, in a normal bone marrow, you can see that there is a small

386
00:22:43.632 --> 00:22:46.792
population of enucleate stage four cell.

387
00:22:47.392 --> 00:22:50.192
In bone metastasis, that population disappears.

388
00:22:50.232 --> 00:22:52.252
They're stuck in this nucleated stage.

389
00:22:52.992 --> 00:22:56.492
And part of the reason is that the genes in the

390
00:22:56.572 --> 00:23:00.252
EBI macrophage that facilitate enucleation, including

391
00:23:00.612 --> 00:23:00.642
Mk,

392
00:23:02.232 --> 00:23:06.032
Xl, Dns2a, often, usually in the

393
00:23:06.112 --> 00:23:08.092
EBI macrophage, they are expressed in high level.

394
00:23:08.732 --> 00:23:12.612
But in those EBI macrophages in bone metastatic mice,

395
00:23:13.512 --> 00:23:15.172
their level of expression reduced.

396
00:23:15.272 --> 00:23:19.252
So the tumor also changes the property of the EBI macrophage,

397
00:23:19.312 --> 00:23:23.212
not only recruit them away from EBI, but also reduce their ability

398
00:23:23.432 --> 00:23:27.212
to facilitate enucleation. Similarly, if you look at

399
00:23:27.252 --> 00:23:31.212
the number of the EBI number by flow cytometry, you can also see

400
00:23:31.232 --> 00:23:34.012
that the EBI number decreased significantly.

401
00:23:35.212 --> 00:23:39.192
And part of the reason is that EBI formation requires adhesion

402
00:23:39.232 --> 00:23:42.312
molecules, including VCAM-1, CD163, and others.

403
00:23:42.492 --> 00:23:44.782
These are two of the three markers.

404
00:23:45.572 --> 00:23:49.492
And again, the EBI macrophage, compared to regular macrophage, have high level

405
00:23:49.532 --> 00:23:51.832
of expression of those adhesion molecules.

406
00:23:51.852 --> 00:23:55.252
But when they are in bone metastasis, those expressions reduce.

407
00:23:55.352 --> 00:23:57.352
Again, soil is changed by the seeds,

408
00:23:58.632 --> 00:24:00.132
and deplete their normal function.

409
00:24:00.192 --> 00:24:03.732
So we then test, is this important for

